---
import CaseStudy from '@/layouts/CaseStudy.astro';

// NOTE: No README — written from the resume line ("A Selenium tool automating
// UMBC student timesheets auto-filling PeopleSoft"). Worth confirming before
// this goes public: that you're comfortable describing credential handling, and
// that nothing here reads as advice to falsify hours.
---

<CaseStudy
	title="ASCAutoPayroll — case study"
	description="A Selenium tool that fills UMBC student timesheets in PeopleSoft from a schedule, turning a weekly form-filling ritual into one command."
	eyebrow="Case study — 2025"
	heading="ASCAutoPayroll"
	lede="Twelve identical form fields, every week, in an interface that predates the students using it. The schedule was already known — the typing was the only variable."
	meta={[
		{ label: 'Stack', value: 'Python · Selenium' },
		{ label: 'Type', value: 'Browser automation' },
		{ label: 'Source', value: 'github.com/arenvista/ASCAutoPayroll', href: 'https://github.com/arenvista/ASCAutoPayroll' }
	]}
>
	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>The problem</h2>
		<p>
			Student employees submit hours through PeopleSoft: log in, navigate several frames deep,
			enter in and out times for each day, save, submit. The shifts are usually the same every
			week, which makes the whole exercise a transcription job — and one with real
			consequences, since a missed submission means a missed paycheck.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>The approach</h2>
		<p>
			Selenium drives a real browser session, because PeopleSoft has no usable API and its
			interface is built from nested frames and generated element IDs — the kind of page that
			defeats a plain HTTP client but is perfectly navigable if you're pretending to be a
			person.
		</p>
		<p>
			A schedule file describes the recurring shifts. The tool logs in, walks to the timesheet
			for the current pay period, fills each row from that schedule, and stops before
			submission so the hours can be checked by an actual human first.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>Working against a hostile page</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>
				Generated IDs change between renders, so elements are located by structure and label
				rather than by whatever ID the page happened to emit.
			</li>
			<li>
				Every action waits on a condition instead of a timer — PeopleSoft's partial page
				refreshes are unpredictable, and fixed sleeps are how these tools rot.
			</li>
			<li>
				Credentials come from the environment, never the repository, and the session is
				torn down when the run ends.
			</li>
			<li>
				A dry run fills the form and stops, so a broken selector shows up as a wrong-looking
				page rather than a wrong submission.
			</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>What I took away</h2>
		<p>
			The part I'd defend is the stop. It would have been trivial to click submit at the end
			of the run, and marginally more convenient — but a tool that files payroll on your
			behalf is one bad selector away from filing something wrong, silently, on a document
			you're accountable for. Automating the tedium and leaving the confirmation is the whole
			design.
		</p>
	</section>
</CaseStudy>
